comments.body:
The issue here is that your `StructB` type contains a managed `bool` field, which causes it to be treated as a non-blittable type. Since `UnionStruct` contains a field of `StructB`, it too is considered non-blittable. This means that `Marshal.PtrToStructure` will attempt to marshal your type instead of just blitting the data across, resulting in the corruption of your pointer.

For ease of reproduction, here is a managed replacement for the native `test_func` method, which still reproduces the problem:
```cs
static unsafe IntPtr testFunc(int value)
{
    Console.WriteLine(">>> test_func:");
    var a = (StructA*)NativeMemory.Alloc((uint)sizeof(StructA));
    a->X = unchecked((nint)0x7ea33f5000);
    a->Y = unchecked((nint)0x7ea3440000);
    a->Z = unchecked((nint)0x7ea3452c00);
    a->XLength = 555;
    a->YLength = 666;
    a->ZLength = 1010;
    Console.WriteLine($"x = 0x{a->X:X}, y = 0x{a->Y:X}, z = 0x{a->Z:X}, x_length = {a->XLength}, y_length = {a->YLength}, z_length = {a->ZLength}");
    return (IntPtr)a;
}
```

There are a few solutions:
1. Use `*(UnionStruct*)ptr` instead of `Marshal.PtrToStructure`.
2. Change the `bool` field to `byte`, which will cause the types to be considered blittable and no marshaling will occur.
3. Add `[assembly: DisableRuntimeMarshaling]` and use `*(UnionStruct*)ptr` instead of `Marshal.PtrToStructure`.

My personal recommendation would be to go with option 2 and use `*(UnionStruct*)ptr` to read the value.

I think this is expected behaviour, even if it may be a bit confusing.

Think about how the type would be marshaled. Each field will be written in order. The marshaller normalizes booleans to `0` (`false`) or `1` (`true`).

They are also marshaled as a Win32 `BOOL` by default, which is a 32-bit integer (so it actually needs `[MarshalAs(UnmanagedType.U1)]` to have a matching layout with native).

This means that if your pointer overlaps with a `bool`, the overlapping byte will be normalized, corrupting the value once the marshaller starts marshaling `StructB`.

To help with understanding the problem, you can try performing the marshaling yourself. Define `StructB` as:
```cs
[StructLayout(LayoutKind.Sequential)]
internal struct StructB
{
    internal IntPtr Data;
    internal uint DataLength;
    internal int Flag; // Win32 BOOL = int
}
```
And then read the value with:
```cs
var unmanagedStruct = *(UnionStruct*)ptr;

// normalize the bool
unmanagedStruct.B.Flag = unmanagedStruct.B.Flag != 0 ? 1 : 0;
```
And you will see the same pointer corruption.
As a result, you can actually "hide" the problem by defining `UnionStruct` like this:
```cs
[StructLayout(LayoutKind.Explicit)]
internal struct UnionStruct
{
    [FieldOffset(0)]
    internal StructB B;
    [FieldOffset(0)]
    internal StructA A;
}
```
Because `StructB` is marshaled first, you won't see the pointer corruption.

```
  struct {
    unsigned char *data;
    unsigned int size;
    bool flag;
  } B;
```
Note that your managed definition of B does not match this structure. Size of `bool` is likely 1 byte in your C/C++ compiler. The default marshalling for `bool` assumes that the size is 4 bytes. This mismatch is contributing to the confusing behavior that you are seeing.

Manual marshalling that @DaZombieKiller suggested is the best way to avoid problems like this for more complex structs with unions, etc. You should use `byte` as managed equivalent for unmanaged `bool`.

Also, take a look at `DisableRuntimeMarshallingAttribute` that is new in .NET 7.

