### Description
Consider the following code.
```
    class Program
    {
		static void Main(string[] args)
		{
			var ci = new CultureInfo("ar"); // Arabic Culture.
			Thread.CurrentThread.CurrentCulture = ci;
			Thread.CurrentThread.CurrentUICulture = ci;
			float a = 1.2343f;
			//Turn a float number into a string with the format X.XXXXX
			string floatNumberString = string.Format("{0:0.######}", a);
			Console.WriteLine("float number string presentation: " + floatNumberString);
			Console.WriteLine("is ASCII string ? " + IsAsciiString(floatNumberString));
		}
		public static bool IsAsciiString(string input)
		{
			for (int i = 0; i < input.Length; ++i)
			{
				char c = input[i];
				if (((int)c) > 127)
				{
					Console.WriteLine("Character '" + c + "'(hex value " + ((int)c).ToString("X") +  ") + at index " + i + " is not ASCII");
					return false;
				}
			}
			return true;
		}
	}
```
If running in the code in windows and linux, we get 2 different outputs:

Windows Output:
```
float number string presentation: 1.2343
is ASCII string ? ? True
```
Linux Output:
```
float number string presentation: 12343
Character ''(hex value 66B) + at index 1 is not ASCII
is ASCII string ? ? False
```
The call string.Format("{0:0.######}", a)  under Arabic culture, yields two different string interpretations of the same float number under 2 different platforms (Window vs Unix). In windows, under Arabic culture, the decimal point is converted into an ascii character (.colon). In contrast, in Linux, the decimal point is converted into an unicode character ( Arabic decimal separator).

### Configuration

* Which version of .NET is the code running on? .Net Core 3.1
* What OS and version, and what distro if applicable? Windows and Linux.

