### Description

If `TcpClient.ConnectAsync` is called from a threadpool thread, when the network is down, waiting on the task object will cause a  deadlock. 

### Configuration

* Which version of .NET is the code running on? dotnetcore 3.1
* What OS and version, and what distro if applicable? Windows 10, x64, 20H2
* What is the architecture (x64, x86, ARM, ARM64)? x64
* Do you know whether it is specific to that configuration? N/A
* If you're using Blazor, which web browser(s) do you see this issue in? N/A


### Regression?

Unsure if this worked in previous builds. 

### Other information

Here's is some sample code that demonstrates the problem:
```C#
using System;
using System.Net.Sockets;
using System.Threading.Tasks;
using System.Threading;

namespace DotNetNetworkingBug
{
    class Program
    {
        static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            Console.WriteLine("Disconnect from the network before running this test.");
            System.Console.WriteLine("Otherwise this will not repro");

            // we're going to have the main thread do things while the behavior happens on
            // a background thread, to simulate what we see in our code, as the issue 
            // happens when the method is fired from a Process exit event handler.

            Task.Factory.StartNew(FireSyncCompletionCallback);
            Task.Factory.StartNew(FireAsyncCompletionCallback);


            for (int i = 0; i < 30; i++)
            {
                Thread.Sleep(1000);
                System.Console.WriteLine($"Program has been running for {i} seconds...");
            }

            System.Console.WriteLine("Program Completed");

        }

        static void FireSyncCompletionCallback()
        {
            using (var client = new TcpClient())
            {
                // this does not work, and deadlocks on a worker thread - no output is generated.
                // (this is done here because there is no way to set a connection timeout)
                if (!client.ConnectAsync("bing.com", 80).Wait(3000))
                {
                    System.Console.WriteLine("SYNC: Failed to connect before timeout");
                }
                else {
                    System.Console.WriteLine("SYNC: Connection successful!");
                }
            }
        }

        static async void FireAsyncCompletionCallback()
        {
            using (var client = new TcpClient())
            {
                // this works, and does not deadlock (though it's less readable)
                // it also does not reach the time out - it detects that a problem occurred immediately.
                await Task.WhenAny(new[] {
                    client.ConnectAsync("bing.com", 80),
                    Task.Delay(3000)
                });

                if (!client.Connected)
                {
                    System.Console.WriteLine("ASYNC: Failed to connect before timeout");
                }
                else {
                    System.Console.WriteLine("ASYNC: Connection successful!");
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```

Part of me suspects this might have to do with some async context, but I can't find anything in the documentation that would indicate this. 

The code works as expected (with both callbacks successfully connecting and printing they connected) if the network is working normally.

