```csharp
// Zero the memory
Marshal.Copy(new byte[sizeInBytes], 0, _memoryPtr, sizeInBytes);
```
If you need to zero a block you need `Unsafe.InitBlockUnaligned` (~  memset)

> zeros a 1GB block of memory in less than 2 milliseconds.

You are not measuring the true cost of the operation. The Windows API you have used will just reserve the memory for you, without actually giving it to your process. You will pay the actual cost of zeroing the memory on demand.

The cross-platform way to achieve the same effect via .NET APIs is using anonymous memory mappings. Try this:

```
using System.IO.MemoryMappedFiles;

...

    public unsafe class AllocatedMemory : IDisposable
    {
        MemoryMappedFile _mapping;
        MemoryMappedViewAccessor _accessor;

        public byte* MemoryAddress { get; }

        public AllocatedMemory(int sizeInBytes)
        {           
            _mapping = MemoryMappedFile.CreateNew(null, sizeInBytes);
            _accessor = _mapping.CreateViewAccessor();
            MemoryAddress = (byte*)_accessor.SafeMemoryMappedViewHandle.DangerousGetHandle();
        }

        ~AllocatedMemory()
        {
            Dispose(false);
        }

        public void Dispose()
        {
            Dispose(true);
            GC.SuppressFinalize(this);
        }

        protected virtual void Dispose(bool disposing)
        {
            if (disposing)
            {
                _mapping.Dispose();
                _accessor.Dispose();
            }
        }
    }
```

