> On your specific points, to keep backwards compatibility,  ...  I'm not sure if that would be the end of the world though. 

It's not the end of the world for sure, but it's generally the end of a feature. :smile:

Back compat, love or hate it, is king.  Every time you break compat in the language, even in the smallest most esoteric ways, you break customers.  Typically a lot of customers. 

> Concrete overloads would be able to safely add nocapture in a covariant fashion I think, but any call through "object" would have to keep the current API (and assume ToString could in theory capture)

An overload of a nocapture must maintain the nocapture semantics.  Otherwise it's possible to violate nocapture rules by capturing 'this' in an override of `ToString`.  

Or in shorter: an override can add nocapture but it cannot remove it. 

> I'm not sure I agree with your delegate example (or I may be misunderstanding). 

Based on your example you seem to have a grasp of the problem I was pointing out.  The nocapture is essentially viral and the annotation on the delegate essentially has to match the annotation of the caller.  

It's actually a bit more viral than the sample alludes to.  Think about the problem of type checking a method marked as nocapture.  So far we've only discussed it in terms of the `this` parameter.  Essentially a method marked as nocapture must ensure only the `this` value isn't captured.  Yet the way you've written the delegate sample implies it's actually more restrictive.  

Look deeper into the delegate type and you'll see a `class` with roughly the following outline:

``` csharp
class Delegate {
  private object _target;
  private IntPtr _method;

  public object Target => _target;
  public IntPtr Method => _method;

  protected Delegate(object target, IntPtr method) {
    _target = target;
    _method = method;
  }
}
```

In order for `nocapture Func<string>` to be safe in your sample it must ensure that both `this` and `_target` are not captured.  Otherwise I could escape a nocapture object trivially by doing the following:

``` csharp
nocapture X local = ...;
Func<string> func = local.ToString;
X local2 = func.Target;
```

For the sample you wrote to type check it would imply that nocapture must ensure that `this` and all reachable references from `this` are not captured.  That's downright draconian and falls apart very quickly in more complex types: most notably collections and enumeration. 

Solving that problem more elegantly requires a parametric polymorphism solution.  Essentially a way to mark fields and members as nocapture if the caller is also nocapture.  It works and can type check pretty reasonably but it's also a bit more advanced than the average C# user is used to .

