@jkotas, as a coreclr guy what do you think?

Looks like an issue in the implementation of TypeBuilder. We get caught in a loop in `TypeBuilder.IsSubclassOf`:


```cs
public override bool IsSubclassOf(Type c)
{
    Type p = this;

    if (TypeBuilder.IsTypeEqual(p, c))
        return false;

    p = p.BaseType;

    while (p != null)
    {
        if (TypeBuilder.IsTypeEqual(p, c))
            return true;

        p = p.BaseType;
    }

    return false;
}
```

But there are more complex types than the case in which `p.BaseType == p`. E.g. circularity:
```cs
[Fact]
public void SetParent_BasicCircularity()
{
    ModuleBuilder module = Helpers.DynamicModule();

    TypeBuilder typeA = module.DefineType("A");
    TypeBuilder typeB = module.DefineType("B");

    typeA.SetParent(typeB.AsType());
    typeB.SetParent(typeA.AsType());

    typeA.CreateTypeInfo();

    // We never get here.
}

[Fact]
public void SetParent_AdvancedCircularity()
{
    ModuleBuilder module = Helpers.DynamicModule();

    TypeBuilder typeA = module.DefineType("A");
    TypeBuilder typeB = module.DefineType("B");
    TypeBuilder typeC = module.DefineType("C");

    typeA.SetParent(typeC.AsType());
    typeB.SetParent(typeA.AsType());
    typeC.SetParent(typeB.AsType());

    typeA.CreateTypeInfo();

    // We never get here.
}
```

A fix would be to change the code for `TypeBuilder.IsSubclassOfType` to:
```cs
public bool IsSubclassOfType(CustomType c)
{
    CustomType original = this;
    CustomType p = this;

    if (Equal(p, c))
        return false;

    p = p.BaseType;

    while (p != null)
    {
        if (Equal(p, c))
            return true;
        if (ReferenceEquals(p, original))
            throw new InvalidOperationException("Circular!?!?");

        p = p.BaseType;
    }

    return false;
}
```

@jkotas this is actually a managed code issue rather than unmanaged. Maybe some kind of `InvalidOperationException` would be a good idea.

EDIT:
Actually this wouldn't work for the following case:
```cs
    CustomType a = new CustomType("a");
    CustomType b = new CustomType("b");
    CustomType c = new CustomType("c");

    a.BaseType = b;
    b.BaseType = a;
    c.BaseType = b; // Go into a circular dependency
```

Or you can be circular via generic (`class G<T> : G<G<T>>`):

```
TypeBuilder type = module.DefineType("Type");
type.DefineGenericParameters("T");
type.SetParent(type.MakeGenericType(type));
type.CreateTypeInfo();
```

There are many types of cycles and other invalid structures that you can create using Reflection.Emit. I do not think it is practical to check for them in the Reflection.Emit APIs. It would basically mean building PEVerify tool into the Reflection.Emit APIs somehow.

